`crates/` is the workspace root holding eight independent crates that together form the `.context/` tooling ecosystem: generation, verification, sandboxed execution, and consumption of `.ctx`/`rollup.ctx` documents plus a separate status/backlog tool. There is no shared code at this level — each crate is a standalone binary (plus library surface in some cases) with its own error type, CLI, and test suite; this directory itself is just a Cargo workspace container.

The crates split into a content-lifecycle group and independent utilities. `ctx-summarize` writes `.ctx`/`rollup.ctx` files (leaf-before-rollup ordering); `ctx-scan` maintains the hash-based staleness mirror deciding what needs summarizing and shares the `cpath` layout convention with it explicitly; `ctx-context` reads and serves the resulting chain read-only, never writing. `ctx-core` supplies pure, dependency-free primitives (denylist, hash-sidecar schema, STATUS.md codec) that other crates may depend on. `ctx-cage` sandboxes agent runs used by `ctx-summarize`/`ctx-brief`; `ctx-verify` independently checks repo health via its own `Runner` abstraction. `ctx-brief` and `ctx-status` are adjacent tools: `ctx-brief` generates executor briefs (including a `status_table` reader), and `ctx-status` owns `docs/status.json`/`STATUS.md`, whose markdown output format `ctx-brief` consumes directly — a rendering change in one requires checking the other.

Across the suite, one convention recurs: every crate pairs its `src/` implementation with a `tests/` directory using hermetic fakes (`FakeFs`, `FakeClaude`, `FakeEnv`, `StubAgent`, `RecordingAgent`) rather than real subprocesses/filesystems, and each crate's rollup calls out that the fakes must be kept in sync with the real trait/struct shapes they stand in for — this is a workspace-wide pattern, not a single crate's quirk.

No `intent.md` exists for this directory, so no divergence can be assessed.